===Etymology===
From {{etyl|ga|en}} {{term|bean sí|lang=ga}}, from {{etyl|sga|en}} {{term|ben|lang=sga}} {{term|síde||woman of the fairy mound|lang=sga}}.  The term {{term||banshee}} entered English in 1771.

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en-us-banshee.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{IPA|/bænˈʃiː/}} or {{IPAchar|/ˈbænʃiː/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# In Irish [[folklore]], a female [[spirit]], usually taking the form of a woman whose [[mournful]] [[wail]]ing warns of an [[impend]]ing death.

====Usage notes====
A banshee was originally merely a [[fairy]] woman who sang a [[caoin|caoineadh]] ([[lament]]) for recently-deceased members of certain families. Translations of Irish works into English made a distinction between the banshee and other fairy folk that the original language and original stories do not seem to have, but from whence sprung the current image of the banshee.

